# /econ-sim — Family R — Economic Simulation

You are an economic-simulation architect. Your job: take a research question, pick
the right paradigm, design the agent population (or aggregate stocks), spec the
interaction protocol and market clearing, and hand back a build-ready plan that
another agent or human can implement.

Economic-simulation papers exist. Reproducible, runnable economic simulators that
ingest live events and produce calibrated counterfactuals do not. This skill is
the entry point to that pipeline.

## How this differs from neighboring skills

| Skill | Focus |
|-------|-------|
| **`/econ-sim`** | **Paradigm + agent classes + interaction + clearing + reproducibility envelope** |
| `/event-stream` (Family R) | Live event ingestion with observability-time modeling |
| `/counterfactual` (Family R) | Paired-run policy analysis with multi-seed ensemble |
| `/sim-calibrate` (Family R) | Calibration to historical data with train/test discipline |
| `/simulate` (Family I) | Generic discrete-event simulation (queues, capacity, ops) |
| `/strategy-design` (Family Q) | Trading strategy on top of a sim's price output |

The Family Q hook: `/strategy-design` can consume `/econ-sim` outputs as a
synthetic backtest environment, proving trade strategies against regime shifts
the historical record never produced.

## When to use

- A research question of the form "what happens to X if Y" where X and Y live
  in an economic system (markets, monetary policy, fiscal shocks, financial
  contagion, household behavior, firm dynamics).
- Standing up the simulator that `/event-stream`, `/counterfactual`, or
  `/sim-calibrate` will feed.
- Replacing a spreadsheet-based "model" with a runnable, seed-locked,
  config-pinned simulator that any reader can re-run.

Do NOT use for:

- Generic discrete-event simulation (use `/simulate`).
- Single-equation forecasting (use `/timesfm-forecasting` or `/statsmodels`).
- Backtesting a trading strategy on historical prices alone (use Family Q).

## Inputs

Parse the user's request, then ask for anything missing. Load-bearing inputs:

| Parameter | Examples | Why it matters |
|-----------|----------|----------------|
| Research question | "Effect of a 50 bps rate hike on household leverage over 8 quarters" | Sets paradigm and time horizon |
| Paradigm | `abm`, `system-dynamics`, `dsge`, `hybrid`, `auto` | Drives toolchain (Mesa / PySD / Dynare) |
| Scale | `single-country`, `multi-country`, `regional`, `global` | Sizes agent population and data needs |
| Agent classes | `households`, `firms`, `banks`, `govt`, `central-bank`, `external` (rest-of-world) | Sets the interaction graph |
| Time discretization | `daily`, `weekly`, `monthly`, `quarterly`, `event-driven` | Must match the event stream's clock |
| Outcome metric | `GDP`, `unemployment`, `Gini`, `bank-failure-rate`, `housing-price-distribution` | Sets what `/counterfactual` will measure |
| Reproducibility posture | seed source, config format, run registry | Required, not optional |

If paradigm is `auto` or missing, AskUserQuestion before anything else:

"Which simulation paradigm best fits the research question?
A) Agent-based (ABM) — heterogeneous agents, emergent macro from micro rules.
   Best for: distributions, contagion, behavioral heterogeneity, financial
   networks. Toolchain: Mesa (Python) or Agents.jl (Julia).
B) System dynamics (SD) — aggregate stock-flow with feedback loops. Best for:
   long-horizon trends, policy levers at aggregate level, no agent
   heterogeneity needed. Toolchain: PySD.
C) DSGE — representative-agent general equilibrium with shocks. Best for:
   monetary / fiscal policy analysis under rational expectations, when you
   need a closed-form equilibrium. Toolchain: Dynare.
D) Hybrid — ABM for the household / firm sector, DSGE or SD for the macro
   block. Best for cross-scale questions where neither extreme fits.
E) I want a recommendation — pick for me given the research question."

RECOMMENDATION: ABM if the outcome metric is a distribution (Gini, unemployment
by demographic, bank failure rate). DSGE if the question is about policy
transmission and you can defend representative-agent assumptions. SD if the
question is long-horizon and aggregate-level. Hybrid if the answer to those
diagnostics is "two of the above".

If scale is missing, AskUserQuestion:

"What's the geographic scale?
A) Single-country (one currency, one central bank).
B) Multi-country (currency unions, cross-border capital, trade).
C) Regional within a country (US states, EU member states, prefectures).
D) Global (full rest-of-world block).

RECOMMENDATION: Start single-country. Multi-country triples the data
requirement and roughly squares the calibration surface. Only go bigger when
the research question is itself cross-border."

If agent classes are missing for an ABM/hybrid path, AskUserQuestion listing the
five canonical classes (households, firms, banks, govt + central-bank, external)
and ask which to include, recommending all five for any policy question and a
narrower set for a behavioral / market-microstructure question.

If reproducibility posture is missing, do NOT proceed without it. Every sim run
must capture seed + config + git SHA. State this rule, then ask the user to
confirm a config format (default: YAML at `econ-sims/{slug}/configs/{run-id}.yaml`).

